 England"},"en":{"1355–1387":"1355–1387","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1404":"1404","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1371":"1371","Wheltrough, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Davenport","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire): habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Davenport, from the Dane river (apparently named with a Celtic cognate of Middle Welsh <i>dafnu</i> ‘to drop, to trickle’) + Old English <i>port</i> ‘market town’.","Irish: in Tipperary, this is an English surname adopted by bearers of Munster Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donndubhartach</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’ + <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>artach</i> ‘nobleman’.","History: John Davenport (died 1670) arrived in Boston, MA, in 1637. He came of an English Cheshire family associated with Capesthorne Hall, near Macclesfield."],"variants":[{"name":"Devenport","meanings":["English and Irish (Lancashire): variant of   Davenport  . The spelling <b>Devonport</b> is found in Ireland and it may have been this form which gave rise to <i>Devenport</i>."]},{"name":"Dunworth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Eamon, Niall.","Irish: adopted in Ireland by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Donndubhartaigh</b> (see   Davenport   2).","English: perhaps a variant of <b>Dungworth</b>, see   Dunsworth  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘Morning dew’; also ‘generosity’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Davenport was born in 1355, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Sir Thomas Leigh in 1371. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1387, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 32."},"et":{"1355–1387":"1355–1387","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1404":"1404","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1